Meta-análise

We fitted a model for each biomarker. In each model, we used the following variables/moderators: Type of exposure (3 levels); NSAID (3 levels), Dose (2 levels), and Exposure (2 levels).

We controlled the variance for the different papers and fish species.

The chosen measure to model the difference between treatment and control was the log response ratio (lnRR)

\[ \text{lnRR} = \log (\text{Response Ratio}) = \log \Big(\frac{\text{Treatment}}{\text{Control}}\Big). \]

The log transformation is applied to have a sampling distribution centered around zero (useful to get more reliable p-values).

Below, we have the model results. Global effect means a model without decomposing the lnRR by any moderator. SE means the standard error (the uncertainty around the lnRR estimate). ci.lb and ci.up are the lower and upper bounds of a 95% confidence interval for the lnRR. Finally, pval is the p-value (in red, all p-values \(\leq\) 0.05).

Everything that is present in the table, now visually:

The dots are the mean lnRR and the horizontal lines are the 95% confidence intervals.

Another graphs that we can do are the caterpillar and the orchard plots. In these graphs, instead of looking at the mean lnRR, we look at each lnRR.

Perform those plots to each biomarker and moderator is unviable. Thus, we choose to perform for the NSAID at the GST biomarker (where we have the biggest confidence interval). k means the number of effects/lines in the dataset.

Besides all that, we also have some standard measures/metrics in a meta-analysis. They are:

  • Q: Cochran’s test statistic for the residual heterogeneity, approximated from a chi-square distribution;

  • \(Q_{M}\): if the variables/moderators are statistically significant;

  • \(R^{2}\): the proportion of the (response) variance/heterogeneity that’s explained by the moderator(s);

  • \(I^{2}\): the estimated amount of heterogeneity relative to the total amount of variance in the observed effects;

  • \(\tau^{2}\): estimated amount of residual heterogeneity.

In red, all significant p-values (\(\leq\) 0.05).

Also, we can make the funnel plots to evaluate some possible publication bias. The desired behavior is all points symmetrically dispersed around zero, and all (ideally) in the white background region.

Referências

The statistical analysis was performed with the R language and environment for statistical computing (R Core Team, 2021). Barplots and percentage computations were used to describe and summarize the qualitative variables. A meta-analysis (Viechtbauer, 2010) was performed for each biomarker to understand and summarize the findings of the articles, in terms of type of exposure; NSAID; dose; and exposure. The main R packages used in this analysis were: {dplyr} (Wickham et al., 2021), {tidyr} (Wickham, 2021), {stringr} (Wickham, 2019), {ggplot2} (Wickham, 2016), {purrr} (Henry and Wickham, 2020), {metafor} (Viechtbauer, 2010), and {orchaRd} (Noble, 2022).

R Core Team (2021). R: A language and environment for statistical computing. R Foundation for Statistical Computing, Vienna, Austria. URL https://www.R-project.org/

Wickham, H., François, R., Henry, L., Müller, K. (2021). dplyr: A Grammar of Data Manipulation. R package version 1.0.7. https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=dplyr

Wickham, H. (2021). tidyr: Tidy Messy Data. R package version 1.1.3. https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=tidyr

Wickham, H. (2019). stringr: Simple, Consistent Wrappers for Common String Operations. R package version 1.4.0. https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=stringr

Wickham, H. (2016). ggplot2: Elegant Graphics for Data Analysis. Springer-Verlag New York

Henry, L., Wickham, H. (2020). purrr: Functional Programming Tools. R package version 0.3.4. https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=purrr

Viechtbauer, W. (2010). Conducting meta-analyses in R with the metafor package. Journal of Statistical Software, 36(3), 1-48. https://doi.org/10.18637/jss.v036.i03

Noble, D. (2022). orchaRd: Orchard Plots and Prediction Intervals for Meta-analysis. R package version 0.0.0.9000.
